TASK 1 – Depth-First Search (source = A)
  Reference: Sedgewick & Wayne, Algorithms 4th ed., p. 537


The DFS algorithm (Sedgewick) maintains a boolean array marked[]
and an integer array edgeTo[].  When a vertex v is first reached,
marked[v] is set to true and dfs(v) recurses through v's adjacency
list in the order given, skipping any already-marked neighbour.

--- Recursive trace ---

dfs(A)
  marked[A] = true                        → Visit A
  Adjacency list of A: C, B, D
  ├─ C not marked → edgeTo[C] = A
  │  dfs(C)
  │    marked[C] = true                   → Visit C
  │    Adjacency list of C: A, B, D
  │    ├─ A marked → skip
  │    ├─ B not marked → edgeTo[B] = C
  │    │  dfs(B)
  │    │    marked[B] = true              → Visit B
  │    │    Adjacency list of B: A, C, E, G
  │    │    ├─ A marked → skip
  │    │    ├─ C marked → skip
  │    │    ├─ E not marked → edgeTo[E] = B
  │    │    │  dfs(E)
  │    │    │    marked[E] = true         → Visit E
  │    │    │    Adjacency list of E: G, F, B
  │    │    │    ├─ G not marked → edgeTo[G] = E
  │    │    │    │  dfs(G)
  │    │    │    │    marked[G] = true    → Visit G
  │    │    │    │    Adjacency list of G: F, B
  │    │    │    │    ├─ F not marked → edgeTo[F] = G
  │    │    │    │    │  dfs(F)
  │    │    │    │    │    marked[F] = true  → Visit F
  │    │    │    │    │    Adjacency list of F: G, E
  │    │    │    │    │    ├─ G marked → skip
  │    │    │    │    │    └─ E marked → skip
  │    │    │    │    │  return from dfs(F)
  │    │    │    │    └─ B marked → skip
  │    │    │    │  return from dfs(G)
  │    │    │    ├─ F marked → skip
  │    │    │    └─ B marked → skip
  │    │    │  return from dfs(E)
  │    │    └─ G marked → skip
  │    │  return from dfs(B)
  │    └─ D not marked → edgeTo[D] = C
  │       dfs(D)
  │         marked[D] = true              → Visit D
  │         Adjacency list of D: C, A
  │         ├─ C marked → skip
  │         └─ A marked → skip
  │       return from dfs(D)
  │  return from dfs(C)
  ├─ B marked → skip
  └─ D marked → skip
  return from dfs(A)

 DFS visit order
  A → C → B → E → G → F → D

 DFS Tree (edgeTo[]) 
  A – C   (A discovered C)
  C – B   (C discovered B)
  B – E   (B discovered E)
  E – G   (E discovered G)
  G – F   (G discovered F)
  C – D   (C discovered D)


TASK 2 – Breadth-First Search (source = A)
  Reference: Sedgewick & Wayne, Algorithms 4th ed., p. 539


BFS uses a FIFO queue.  The source is enqueued and marked first;
then the algorithm repeatedly dequeues a vertex v, inspects every
neighbour w in v's adjacency list, and enqueues (and marks) each
unmarked w, recording edgeTo[w] = v.

Step-by-step trace

Initialise:
  Enqueue A, marked[A] = true
  Queue: [A]
  marked : {A}

Step 1 – Dequeue A
  Adjacency list of A: C, B, D
    C not marked → marked[C]=true, edgeTo[C]=A, enqueue C
    B not marked → marked[B]=true, edgeTo[B]=A, enqueue B
    D not marked → marked[D]=true, edgeTo[D]=A, enqueue D
  Queue: [C, B, D]
  marked : {A, C, B, D}

Step 2 – Dequeue C
  Adjacency list of C: A, B, D
    A marked → skip
    B marked → skip
    D marked → skip
  Queue: [B, D]

Step 3 – Dequeue B
  Adjacency list of B: A, C, E, G
    A marked → skip
    C marked → skip
    E not marked → marked[E]=true, edgeTo[E]=B, enqueue E
    G not marked → marked[G]=true, edgeTo[G]=B, enqueue G
  Queue: [D, E, G]
  marked : {A, C, B, D, E, G}

Step 4 – Dequeue D
  Adjacency list of D: C, A
    C marked → skip
    A marked → skip
  Queue: [E, G]

Step 5 – Dequeue E
  Adjacency list of E: G, F, B
    G marked → skip
    F not marked → marked[F]=true, edgeTo[F]=E, enqueue F
    B marked → skip
  Queue: [G, F]
  marked : {A, C, B, D, E, G, F}

Step 6 – Dequeue G
  Adjacency list of G: F, B
    F marked → skip
    B marked → skip
  Queue: [F]

Step 7 – Dequeue F
  Adjacency list of F: G, E
    G marked → skip
    E marked → skip
  Queue: []  ← empty, BFS complete

 BFS visit order (order vertices were first enqueued/marked)
  A → C → B → D → E → G → F

 BFS Tree (edgeTo[]) – shortest paths from A 
  A – C   distTo[C] = 1
  A – B   distTo[B] = 1
  A – D   distTo[D] = 1
  B – E   distTo[E] = 2
  B – G   distTo[G] = 2
  E – F   distTo[F] = 3

  Shortest paths from A:
    A → C          (length 1)
    A → B          (length 1)
    A → D          (length 1)
    A → B → E      (length 2)
    A → B → G      (length 2)
    A → B → E → F  (length 3)
